{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608737/1958033101/1377.xml":{"full_text":"A-6\nTHE EVENING STAR, Washington, D. C.\nmoxpat. mabcx si, rasa.\nTEXT OF VETO NOTE\nPresident Lists Points\n,V-\nAgainst Farm Bill\nThe text of President Ei\nsenhower's veto message on\nthe farm bill follows:\nTo the Senate:\nI return herewith, without\nmy approval. Senate Joint Res\nolution 162. I have given earn\nest consideration to the many\nrepresentations made to me\nboth for and against it. It is\nmy judgment that to approve\nthis resolution would be ill-ad\nvised, from the standpoint both\nof the Nation and of our farm\nfamilies as well. It is regret\ntable that for the second time\nin two years the Congress has\nsent me a farmijbiU which I\ncannot in good conscience ap\nprote.\nSpecifically, the Resolution\nX'ould have such consequences,\naa these:\ni. It would pile up more farm\nproducts in Government ware- 1\nhpuaes.\nwould restrict the growth\nof markets.\n3. It would postpone the day\nwhen agriculture can be re\nleased from the strait-jacket\nof controls.\n4. It would by-pass the prob\nlems of the small operator who\nproduces so little for sale price\nsupports have scant meaning.\n5. It would hold up the needed\ntransition to modern parity and\nwould in fact disregard the\nparity principle.\n6. It would be unfair to those\nwinter wheat growers who\nsigned up under the 1958 acre\nage reserve program with the\nunderstanding that the price\nsupports which had then been\nannounced would be the ef\nfective rates.\nNeeds Thaw, Not Freese\nThis resolution would fix\nfarm price supports and farm\nacreage allotments at not less\nthan existing levels. The true\nneed is to relate both price\nsupports and acreage allot\nments to growing market op\nportunities.\nWith regard to Government\ncontrols, what the farm econ\nomy needs is a thaw rather\nthan a big freeze.\nImprovements have been\nmade in farm legislation in re\ncent years. The keys to these\nImprovements have been ex- i\npension of markets and greater\nopportunity for our farm people\nto exercise their own sound\njudgment.\nFears were expressed by some\nthat farm prices might collapse\nwhen high rigid price supports\nwere abandoned. These fears\ndid not materialize. Instead,\nfarm prices rose. This month\nthe index of prices received by\nfanners is 9 per cent above the\nlevel that prevailed in June of\n1955 when high rigid price sup\nport# were last generally in\neffect. The parity ratio now\nstands at \u00a77. up rpolnts from\n'i'Mfct of agriculture is with-'\nout 'production controls and\nWithout price support. This is\ngenerally true of meat animals,\npoultry, and fruits and vege\ntables\nThere is impressive evidence\nthat farmers stand to profit\nfrom less rather than more\ngovernmental intervention. Un\nsupported prices of cattle and\nbogs and unusually strong.\nMany Problems Remain\nDespite these bright spots,\nmany farm problems remain\nto be solved. The price-cost\nsqueeze continues to harrass\nodr farm people. Production\nrestrictions impose a severe\nbturden. Many of our farmers\u2014\nthose on farms not large\nenough to be profitable are\nraming incomes which are\nbelow any generally eccepted\nstandard.\nCotton, wheat, corn and other\nbasic crops have major prob\nlems. Progress in solving the\nproblems of these crops cannot j\nbe made by going backward.\nWe must continue in the direc- j\ntion which the Congress set in\n1954 and indorsed in 1956\nchanges in the direction of\ngreater opportunity for adjust\nments made necessary by our\never-changing agriculture.\nI said, prior to the passage\nof this Resolution, that what it\nproposed would be a turn of 180\ndegrees in the wrong direction.\nAfter reviewing the Resolution\nin its final form. I adhere to\nthis conviction.\nFor the 1957 crop, prices were\nsupported, product by product,\nin accordance with a complex\nset of legislative and adminis\ntrative considerations. The\nsame was true in the establish\nment of acreage allotments. To\ncarry these forward unaltered,\ndespite changes in demand, ini\nsupply, and in surplus stocks.!\nwould be contrary to sound leg\nislative procedures and would\ncompletely disregard economic\nfact.\nCites Past Progress\nNow I want to turn to the\nprogress that has been made\nthrough programs already in\neffect. In recent years a many\nsided attack on farm problems\nhas been launched. Substantial\ngains have been achieved:\nThrough the Rural Develop\nment Program to help those at\nthe low end of the income\nscale.\nThrough market-making ex\nports which last year reached\nan all-time high.\nThrough providing needed\ncredit to family farms.\nThrough sharing our abun\ndance with the needy at home\nand abroad.\nThrough market development\nIn cooperation with producer\norganizations and the food\ntrade.\nThrough surplus reduction,\nwhich has cut down our stocks\nby more than a billion dollars.\nThrough stepped-up research\nto find- new uses for farm\nproducts.\nThrough special programs to\nIncrfase milk consumption.\nThrough expanded long\nrange conservation measures.\nCan Be Helpful\nWhile it is necessary to re\nject the freeze embodied in this\nresolution, the Congress and\nthe Executive Branch can be\nhelpful in other ways.\nA five-point program should\nbe undertaken. Involving vari\nous separate but related actions.\nj Some of these are the re\nsponsibility of the Congress\nI and some are administrative.\nSome call for legislation, while\nample authority already exists\nfor others.\n1. The, old basic law should\nbe revised. On January 16.\n1958, I sent to the Congress\na special message on agri\nculture which recommended\nneeded changes. Many of the\nI I problems will be alleviated if\nthe Congress will act on these\nproposals in this session:\n1 Authority to increase acreage\nallotments up to 50 per cent,\nr and to widen the range within\nwhich price supports may be\nElimination of acreage allot\nments for corn, permitting all\ni corn farmers to plant in ac\ncordance with their best man\nagement decisions, so that price\nI supports would apply to all corn\nI rather than, as the freeze bill\ni would have it. to only about\none acre in seven in the com\nmercial corn area.\ni Abolishment of escalator\nclauses in the law because these\nrigid provisions keep farm peo\npie continually under the\ni shadow of price-depressing sur\npluses.\nExtension of the Agricul\ntural Trade Development and\nAssistance Act. with substantial\nincreased authority to move\ni surplus stocks abroad.\nShifting the price supports\nfor cotton to the average of the\ncrop, the same as for all other\nfarm products.\nThere is opportunity to make\nthese needed changes before\nfail seeding time if the matter'\nis undertaken promptly.\nSees High Levels\n2. When these necessary leg- 1\nislative changes have been\nmade, 1959 acreage allotments!\n.will be established at levels as\nhigh or higher than those pre\nvailing in 1958. Certain statu\ntory provisions which place a\nfloor under acreage allotments\nfor cotton and rice are sched\nuled to expire after the 1958\ncrop. Producers face sharp\nacreage reductions unless the\nlaw is changed. When the Sec\nretary of Agriculture has been\ngiven the necessary authority\nto adjust price support and\nacreage allotments he will set\n1959 allotments at levels at\nleast as high as those in use\nithls year. For cotton and rice\nthese allotments will pe sub\nstantially above the levels\nwhich would otherwise prevail.\n3. When necessary new au\nthorization is provided in keep\ning with my legislative recom- j\nmendatlons, the special export\nprograms for our surplus crops\nwill be enlarged Opportunities\nexist to export, both for dollars\nand through special programs,\nlarge quantities of our staple\ncommodities.\nl Wheat is becoming better\nknown to consumers abroad.\nMarket development and pro\nmotional activities have made\nmore people acquainted with\nthe merits of our many export\nproducts. These commodities\ncan alleviate hunger and need,\nand should be so used.\nNot Offered for Sale\n4. Dairy products acquired\nunder the price support opera\ntion will be used outside the\nregular domestic commercial\nmarket. These products will not\nbe offered for sale in such mar\nkets during the remainder of\ni 1958 at less than 90 per cent of\nparity. While freezing supports\nwould not be a useful step, we\nseek to help the dairy industry\nin other ways.\nTo strengthen markets, the\nbutter, cheese and dry milk ac\nquired under price support will\nbe donated to the school lunch\nprogram, to charitable institu\ntions and to needy persons. Ex\nports will be made when this\ncan appropriately be done.\nSuch inventory management\nwill serve to bolster the market.\nMeanwhile, the administra\ntion will continue to support\nthe special school milk and\narmed services milk programs.\nWe will also support as a fur\nther aid to dairy farmers, the\naccelerated bruccelosis control\nprogram. Stepped up promo\ni tional activity will increase\ni consumption.\nEvery constructive step avail\nable to us will be taken to in\ncrease the use of our whole\nsome dairy products.\nExport Program Planned\n5. An export program for cot\nton, corn and other feed grains,\nsimilar to the present export\n1 program on wheat, will be put\ninto effect. This can be done\n1 without legislation. The effect\nof this program will be to move\nthese products directly from\ncommercial markets to the ex\nport trade without running\nthem through the Commodity\nCredit Corporation. Under the\nwheat export program farmers\nI have obtained broader markets\nand substantial price benefits\nin the marketplace. Marketing\nefficiency has been promoted\nand the amount of wheat which\nhas moved into Government\nchannels has been reduced!\nThe new program for cotton\nand feed grains is expected to\nI have similar effects.\nTo meet the rapidly chang\nmg conditions in agriculture.\nfarmers must be able to make\ntheir own management deci\nl slons on their own farms. They\ni must not have their production\nand prices frozen in an out\ni moded pattern. They must not\n!be made the captives of re- 1\nmw I\n\nTHIS WILL MAKE YOU FEEL OLDER\nRemember Deanna Durbin, the child-singing star of\nthe thirties? Now she\u2019s a 35-year-old matron living\nwith her French husband, movie director Charles\nDavid, in Neauphle-le-Chateau near Paris. She\u2019s\nshown with her 5-year-old son, Peter.\u2014AP Wirephoto.\nLee Defends TV Men's\nPayments of Hotel Bills\nFederal Communications\nCommissioner Robert E. Lee\n'defended to a House subcom\nmittee today the payment of\napproximately $350 of his hotel\nI bills by radio and TV Industry\ni representatives.\nHe said he did Ihot regard\n.those payments on six official\ntrips he made in 1955, 1956 and\n1957 as having put him under\nj obligation or as having been\nintended to influence his deci\nsions. He reported that during\nthe last two years alone he has\nFARM\nContinued From First Page\nfrom the standpoint \u201cboth of\nthe Nation and of our farm\nfamilies as well.\u201d\nGives 6 Reasons for Veto\nHe gave six specific reasons\nfor vetoing thi measure. These\nwere that it would:\n1. Pile up more farm products\nin Government warehouses.\n2. Restrict the growth of mar\nkets.\n3. Postpone \"the day when\nagriculture can be released from\nthe straightjacket of controls.\"\n4. Bypass problems of the\nsmall operator \u201cwho produces\nso little for sale that price sup\nports have scant meaning j\n5. Hold up the needed transi\ntion to modern parity and \"in\ni fact, disregard the parity prin\nciple.\u201d\n6. Be unfair to winter wheat\ngrowers who signed up under\nthe 1958 acreage reserve pro-']\ngram with the understanding\nthat the price supports which\nhad been announced would be\nthe effective rates.\nPoints to Price Rise\nNoting that some people had\nfeared warm prices might col- s\nlapse when high rigid price\nsupports were dropped. Mr. Ei\nsenhower said such fears have\nnot materialized.\n\u201cInstead, farm prices rose,\u201d:\nhe said. \u201cThis month the index\nof prices received by farmers is;\n9 per cent above the level that\nprevailed in June of 1955 when\nhigh rigid price supports were\nlast generally in effect. The\nparity ratio now stands at 87.\nup six points from a year ago.\u201d\nThe President pointed out\nthat, most of agriculture now is 1\noutside of production controls\nand price supports. He said this 1\nis generally true of meat ani\nmals. poultry and fruits and,\nvegetables.\nHe noted that unsupported\nprices on cattle and hogs are\n1 unusually strong.\nSqueeze Continues\nDespite these bright spots.\nMr. Eisenhower said the price\ncost squeeze continues to ha\nrass farmers.\nHe explained that his sug\ngested five-point program as a]\nsubstitute for the vetoed freeze\nbill involved various separate\nbut related actions.\nHis first point urged revision\nof the basic farm law in ac-'\ncord with recommendations he\nsubmitted to Congress in\nspecial message ,asr January\n16. He called particular atten\ntion to proposals which would.\n1. Give authority to increase 1\nacreage allotments up to 50\nper cent, and to widen the'\nrange within which price sup\nports may be provided.\n2. Eliminate acreage allot\nments for corn, permitting all\ncorn farmers to plant in ac- j\ncordance with their best man\nagement decisions, so that price\nsupports would apply to all i\ncorn.\n3. Abolish escalator clauses\nin the law. which he saM \u201ckeep\nfarm people continually under\nthe shadow of price depressing\nsurpluses.\u201d\n4. Extend the surplus dis\nposal law with substantially in\ncreased authority to move sur\nplus stocks abroad.\n5. Shift the price supports\nfor cotton to the average of the\ncrop.\nstricted history: they must be\ngiven freedom to build a\nbrighter future. This can be\ndone if farmers and those who\nserve them will team up in sup\nport of sound legislative and\nadministrative action.\nI DWIGHT D. EISENHOWER\nhad to spend almost $350 of his\nown money on such official\nI trips because the government\nexpense allowance was too\n1 small.\ni\ni Mr. Lee, a Republican mem-\nIber of the FCC since 1953 and\na Government employe since\n1938. was one of the final\nI scheduled witnesses as the\nHouse Legislative Oversight\nSubcommittee neared the close\n,of five weeks of public hear\nings, mainly on the Miami TV\nChannel 10 award. He was\nquestioned today principally in\nconnection with complaints by\nDr. Bernard Schwartz, former\nsubcommittee couryel. that he\nand some of his fellbw commis\nsioners improperly took expense\npayments from persons or com\npanies subject to the jurisdic\ntion of the FCC.\nMrs. McCarthy Present\nMr. Lee\u2019s appearance today\nI coincided with his birthday. In\nthe crowded hearing room were\nMrs. Lee and Mrs. Joseph R.\nMcCarthy, widow of the late\nSenator from Wisconsin.\nAs for the hotel bills, Mr.\nLee explained that in every in\nstance they were incurred dur\ning official trips he made to\nvarious cities to address indus\ntry groups or attend regional\n\u2018conferences. In several in\nstances the bills were paid by.\nthe National Association of\nBroadcasters, which Mr. Lee\nsaid, is not directly subject to\nthe FCC.\nMr. Lee testified, as did sev\neral of his fellow commission\ners last week, that he received\na color television set from the\nindustry, and also received some\nmaintenance.\nThe commission discussed\nI that matter at a meeting sev\neral years ago and agreed\nthat the commissioners prop\nerly could accept color sets, Mr.\nLee recalled. He said that the\nonly things that might be re\ngarded as gifts from industry\nwere a transistor radio from a\ncompany he did not identify,\nand a poinsettia plant and\nphonograph record from Frank\nStanton, head of the Columbia\nBroadcasting System.\n\u201cNot Approached\u201d\nQuestioned about the Miami\nChannel 10 case, Mr. Lee said\nhe had not been approached\n'by any person in or out of\nGovernment. He said he also\nhad never discussed the mat\nter with former Commissioner\nRichard A. Mack except at\ncommission meetings. Mj.\nMack resigned several weeks\nago as a result of disclosures\nthat he accepted loans and\nother financial help from a\nMiami lawyer. Mr. Mack con\ntended this did not influence\nhis vote in the Miami case.\n\u201cMr. Mack made no secret\nof his concern about the Miami\ncase in commission meetings.\u201d\nMr. Lee said. \"But I do not\nrecall he ever said he was\nover the barrel in that case.\nHe seemed to hope that the?\ncommission would make a'\nunamious decision, and he\ndidn't seem to care who got it.\u201d'\nEisenhowers Return,\nAttended David's Party\nBy tht Atsornted Preu\nPresident and Mrs. Eisen\nhower returned to the White\ni House from their Gettysburg\n'farm at 12:10 p.m. today after\nhelping their grandson David\ncelebt-ate his 10th birthday this\nmorning.\nThey made the 80-mlle re\nturn trip by car.\nDavid, the son of Maj. and\nMrs. John Eisenhower, is the\nPresident\u2019s only grandson. The\nboy's parents and three sisters\nalso spent the week end at the\nfarm.\nOfficial business received min\nimum attention over a Friday\nto Monday week end the chief\nexecutive spent at his Gettys\nburg farm. For the most part\nIt was a week end of relaxation\n\u2014the first the Eisenhowers had\nenjoyed at their country home\nsince the new year holidays.\nMr. Eisenhower had to pass\nup golf because of muddy\nSupreme Court\nUpholds Terms\nGiven 2 Reds\nBy HOWARD L. DUTKIN\nStir Stag Walter\nThe Supreme Court today\nupheld three-year prison terms\ngiven two Communist leaders\nfor criminal contempt of court.\nThe two are Oilbert Green\nand Henry Wlnsten.\nThey had \u2018been convicted\nalong with nine other defend\nants on charges of advocating\nthe violent overthrow of the\nGovernment in 1949 in New\nYork.\nThey appealed this convic\ntion but disappeared after the\nSupreme Court upheld their\nconvictions. They avoided ar\nrest for five years afterward.\nSurrendered in \u2019M\nThe contempt sentences given\nthem ,in United States District\nCourt in New York stemmed\nfrom their failure to appear in\nUnited Btates District Court\npursuant to a surrender order\nafter the Supreme Court had\nrejected their appeal.\nThey finally surrendered in\n1956.\nThe three-year contempt\nterms were in addition to the\nfive-year terms for Smith Act\nviolation.\nIn appealing their contempt\nsentences. Green and Winston\nquestioned whether criminal\ncontempt may be punished by\na sentence of more than one\nyear in prison and they argued\nthat there was an' abuse of\ndiscretion in the three-year\nterms. They also denied there\nwas sufficient evidence that\nthey had knowledge of the sur\nrender order.\nTerms Seen Reasonable\nIn affirming the reasonable\nness of the sentences, the Su\npreme Court majority said:\n\u201cFirst, the contempt here\nwas by any standards a most\negregious. Petioners had been\naccorded a fair trial and\n(had been granted bail pending\nreview\n\u201cNevertheless they absconded\nand over 4Vi years of hiding\nj culminated not in a belated rec\nognition of the authority of the\ncourt, but the petitioners\u2019 re\nassertion of Justification for\ndisobeying the surrender\norder.\u201d\nRESPONSE\nContinued From First Page\nSoviet gesture was designed for;\nits propaganda value.\nCongress More Blunt\nComment in Congress put in\nblunter language what the\nState Department said in more\nrestrained fashion.\nChairman Durham, Demo- 1\ncrat of North Carolina, of the 1\nSenate-House Atomic Energy\nCommittee said the Soviet an\nnouncement is \"phony, like\neverything else they have done\nin that line.\u201d\nMr. Durham said the Soviets,\nin 14 tests since last\u2018August,\napparently have tried out all\nthe new types of weapons they\nhave ready for explosion, and\nwould be ready for a halt any-j\nway.\nRepresentative Van Zandt.'\nRepublican of Pennsylvania, i\nsaid. \u201cThis is as phony as it;\ncan be and is merely an attempt\n;to embarrass us.\u201d\nMr. Van Zandt. a member of\nthe Committee on Atomic En\nergy. said it would take the So\nviets a year to evaluate the in\nformation gained in their just\ncompleted series of tests.\nMain U. 8. Points\nThe main paints the Sttae\nDepartment statement sought\nto get over to the world were\nthese:\n1. Russia could cheat with\nout the world knowing as long 1\nas the Kremlin refused to allow\nUnited Nations inspectors to\ni police any ban.\n2. Russia has blocked work\nof the 25-nation U. N. Disarma\nment Commission since last\nfall. The Soviets have refused\nto attend any meetings of this\ngroup, contending its member\nship is stacked in favor of\nWestern countries.\nMan Held on Charge\nOs Killing Brother\nWalter Matthews. 39. of\nSandy Spring, Md., was charged\nwith murder yesterday in the\nshotgun death of his brother. 1\nThe brother, Joshua S. Mat-!\nthews. 43. of the 100 block\nEighth street N.W.. was killed\nshortly after midnight at\nWalter Matthews\u2019 trailer. Mont\ngomery County police said\nWalter Matthews called and;\n>reported that he had shot his!\nbrother.\nThe two men had an argu\nment, police reported.\ngrounds at the Gettysburg\nCountry Club. But he wandered\naround his rolling acre*, did a\nbit of skeet shooting, took the\ni first lady to Palm Sunday\nchurch services, and enjoyed\nthe company of David and\nthree granddaughters.\nMeanwhile, the White House\nsaid there has been no decision\nyet as to where the Eisenhow\ners will spend Easter Sunday.\nPress Secretary James C.\nHagerty told newsmen there is\nnothing definite on whether the\nPresident will go to Augusta.\nGa., next week for a golfing va\ncation.\nIn other years since he took\noffice Mr. Eisenhower has gone\nto Augusta for a week or 10\ndays immediately after the\nannual Masters tournament at\nthe Augusta National Golf Club\ncourse.\nThe 1950 tournament Is\nscheduled to end next Sunday. l\nRESCUED FROM SIERRA SNOWS\u2014These three Stanford University\nstudents and a fourth companion have been rescued by helicopter from\nthe deep snow of a rugged area of California\u2019s Sierra Nevada Mountains,\n1 1.000 feet above sea level. The girls are Margaret Meyer, 21 (center),\nof Seattie, and Lenore Lamb, 21 (right), of Orinda, Calif. The boy is\nBill Pope, 21, of San Francisco. Also saved was Michael M. Roberts, 21,\nof Neenah, Wis.\u2014AP Wirephoto.\nECONOMIC\nCratlaaed From First Page\nwalks, bridges, airports and\nmunicipal building projects.\nSenator Fulbrlght argued\nthat present limitations made\nthe loans attractive only to\nsmall towns for water and\nsewer systems.\nFreezing of Funds Opposed\nSenator Mansfield of Mon\ntana. acting Democratic leader.\nIntroduced a bill to make it un\nlawful for the Budget Bureau\nto impound funds appropriated\nby Congress. He said the pres\nent administration has frozen\nfunds already available for\nbuilding National Guard arm\nories and that the Truman ad\nministration once did the same\nthing after Congress appropri\nated money for a 70-group Air\nForce.\nSenator Mansfield said $32.3\nmillion is available for armories,\nbut the Budget Bureau has re\nleased only $lO million.\nToday\u2019s developments at the\nCapitol came as Democrats and'\nRepublicans entered claims for i\ncredit for anti-recession ac\ntions.\nThe Democrats said things\nthey have done and are doing\n\u201cwill in all probability bring\nthe Eisenhower administration\nthrough its second recession.\":\nBut the Republicans said that]\nactions taken or requested by\nthe administration itself\u2014they\nmentioned 50 steps involving $9\nbillion\u2014will have \"Immeasur\nable\" impact.\nV. S. Buying Bill Pastes\nThe House, meanwhile, by\nvoice vote, quickly passed an\nadministration-sponsored bill\nito authorize the speed-up in\n(purchases of 1840 million in\ncivilian items for the Govern-'\nment.\nAmid the political jockeying,\nthe House moved toward pas\nsage. probably today, of an'\nadministration sponsored bill!\nto authorise a speed-up in\npurchases of SB4O million in;\ncivilian items for the govern-!\nment.\nMeanwhile, members of Con\ngress offered new recovery pro\nposals and pushed for action on\npending anti-recession legis\nlation.\nAnd there was new talk of!\ntax cutting. Dr. Gabriel Hauge,;\nPresident Eisenhower's top\neconomic adviser, said the ad\nministration is neither for nor\nagainst a cut at this point.\nHe said it will make its deci\nsion. perhaps in several weeks,\nafter a broad study of how the\neconomy is faring under the\nspur of recovery measures al\nready taken.\nThe week end brought rival\nRepublican and Democratic\nbids for voter favor on the\nrecovery issue.\nOn Saturday. Senate Repub\nlican leader Knowland of Cali\nfornia and House G. O. P.\nleader Martin of Massachu\nsetts put out a joint statement\nnoting 29 antirecession steps\nthe Eisenhower administration\nhas taken by itself and 21 more\nhow would YOU like some\nUNEARNED\nJust let your money do the earning! Open your account at\nEquitable, then save some of your earned income every pay\nday. Your savings will start working for you all by them\nselves\u2014with Equitable\u2019s generous dividends helping, of course.\nAll you have to do is sit back and watch your money grow.\n@Our 78 years of experience do the trick!\nSTABILITY IS OUR GREATEST ASSET\nEQUITABLE\nSavings and Loan Association\n915 F Street N.W. NAtional 8-1741\nWHEATON BRANCH\u2014 I 1433 GEORGIA AVE.... LOckwood 4-0001\nEdward L. McAleer, President\nit has asked Congress to\napprove.\nBenator Knowland and Rep\nresentative Martin said stepped\nup spending actions involve\nmore than $9 billion and that\nas these actions \"make them\nselves felt across the Nation,\nthe dollar Impact of the impe\ntus will be immeasurable.\u201d\nThey said there is \"no leaf\nraking make-work in the ad\nministration program,\u201d adding\nthat \u201cthe actions are designed\nto create meaningful activity\nsoon.\u201d\nThe Democratic Digest, in its\nSeen swarming termites?\n*gf v NX\nDANGER\nLOOK OUT!\nM.\nEvery year termites cause thousands of dollars\u2019 worth of\nproperty damage m this area alone. Hidden termites may\nbe undermining your home right now and you not\nknow it!\nDON\u2019T LIT IT HAPPEN TO YOUI\nCall Terminix\u2014world's largest in termite control for over\na quarter of a century. Check Terminix service's insured\nguarantee.* No other organization has such a long record\nof proved successful results. Stop termites now\u2014avoid\ncostly damage later! Call Terminix today.\n*GuaranMe4 by your local Terminix concern and E. L. Brae* CO.\nand insured by Sun Insurance Office, Ltd.\nColl Terminix, DUpont 7-2255\nfor a free home inspection by expert*\nTERMINIX\nConnecticut Ave. and S N.W.\nWorld's Largest in Termite Control\nApril Issue released yesterday,\nspoke of what it called \u201cthe\nstrange spectacle of adminis\ntration leaders and Republican\ncongressional members saying\n\u2018me too\u2019 to the Democratic\nanti-recession programs.\u201d\nThe Digest, official publica\ntion of the Democratic National\nCommittee, said Congress has\nbeen \u201csubmerged in Democratic\nproposals to insure full em\nployment. to neutralize the long\nharmful effects of the adminis\ntration\u2019s tight money policies.\u201d","height":"28695","width":"18639"}}
